Finally, Samsung might have some flip-phone competition. Oppo today announced the Find N2 Flip, a clamshell foldable with a massive 3.26" AMOLED cover display -- bigger even than the Razr's -- and a primary display whose crease is as close to invisible as any phone's ever gotten. The phone will launch for £850 in the UK, about £50 less than Samsung charges for the Flip 4, and it will come with 4 years of guaranteed platform updates. 

But the Find N2 isn't an automatic home run. The software doesn't yet take full advantage of the big cover display canvas, instead merely aping Samsung's widgets at launch. The MediaTek 9000+ chipset might put off the spec seekers, and the camera, while capable, has some frustrating limitations. 

I'll cover those and all the usual details in my full review dropping on YouTube this weekend. Meanwhile, stay tuned for a live Q&A here -- and let me know if you'd buy the Find N2 Flip in the comments!

I'll never be an audiophile, but I do care about aesthetics in my earbuds. So the $149 price tag on @nothing's ear (2) doesn't put me off. In a sea of white Airpods and Samsung/Pixel buds that seem almost shy in their design, Nothing's retro-chic clear-tech look stands out (without being too loud about things).

And while the ear (1) did okay on the audio side, the sequel really brought some solid refinements. ANC, the weakest point of the prior model, actually cancels noise pretty well this year. The customizable tap controls have been converted into squeeze inputs for more reliable feedback. And the case is a little bit smaller (if a little more generic-looking).

About the only complaint I have is the Nothing app, which fights with Android's Bluetooth dialog on first pairing. If you often switch phones, that'll be an annoyance. Otherwise, there's not much reason I can see not to buy these.

The Nothing ear (2) buds are on sale now.

“Will I hurt my folding phone if I flip it open as hard as I can?”

“Why do different foldables have different-looking creases?”

“How are folding phones even possible?”

The answer to all these questions comes down, mostly, to the same ancient technology that makes your laptops, your cabinets … even your front door work: the good old-fashioned hinge.

Recently, Oppo gave me the opportunity to learn everything I could learn about the hinges inside its Find N2 and Find N2 Flip folding phones – and today on Into The Fold, I’m taking an up-close look at them, to see what they can teach us about what it takes to fold a phone!

So it's no small thing to say that the Oppo Find X6 Pro has *completely* turned me around. I started shooting portraits at the @johndeere Tech Summit in Austin this week and could. not. stop.

From the usual tech-blogger suspects to the people who design and build the high-tech farm equipment of the future, this camera somehow simultaneously preserves the truth of a person, while adding just enough photographic sleight of hand to make you ask the old question: "these came from a PHONE?!"

Is it the Hasselblad color tuning? The lenses? The sensors? Some combination of all three, no doubt (plus, I admit: it doesn't hurt to hang with photogenic people in idyllic settings 😄).

We spend a lot of time talking about the phones we carry, but it’s rare that we think about the networks that make them work.

When Verizon invited me to Kansas City, MO for something related to the NFL Draft, I almost said no (I barely know what the NFL even is, to say nothing of a “Draft”). But then Verizon told me *why* it invited me: Kansas City will see 300,000 people flood its borders for the event, and every wireless carrier is bolstering its network to prepare for the crush!

So I spent a day being reintroduced to hardware like “Cells on Wheels” (COWs) and “Cells On Light Trucks” (COLTs), and seeing for the first time Verizon’s version of the SPOT (Satellite Picocell On Trailer) and THOR (Tactical Humanitarian Operations Response). I saw a robot dog that becomes a roving WiFi hotspot, and I re-learned just how big a cell site antenna really is – while 65 feet underground in the Missouri cavern where Verizon keeps its emergency equipment safe from tornadoes. And I saw just how big a cable doesn’t need to be, even when it’s carrying thousands of voice and data calls.

Check out my VZ Network Tour story (pinned in my Highlights) for the whole adventure!

Disclosure: Verizon provided travel and lodging for the network tour. No compensation or editorial input.

#verizon #verizonresponse #verizonresponseteam #verizonfrontline #cellular #paidtravel

To most, Marques Brownlee is @MKBHD: tech-YouTube heavyweight and ultimate flinger of Ultimate frisbees. To me, he's the friendly fellow geek I met at a Samsung event 11 years ago – a dude who was already well on his way to stardom, yet as kind and accessible as he remains today. I’ve always been too much of a Sperry stan/Allbirds advocate to even notice Atoms … but I gotta say, these have been pretty cozy over the past few days of wear. Stretch laces let me slip ‘em on and off; lots of support; comfy 8mm heel-to-toe drop (whatever that means); and mesh up top to keep the foot sweat down, which, ya know … that's always good, right? Nope, not a paid spot … and I didn't do it for the free shoes either. I just love seeing a good guy do well. He is, and he does. Congrats on the kicks, Marques.

Ten weeks after its European release, the Oppo Find N2 Flip is still evolving. In the "things you can touch" department: Oppo partnered with Italian industrial-design firm Qeeboo on limited-edition cases and downloadable animated wallpapers to match. (As you know, I'm not much of a case guy, but I do appreciate when OEMs go the extra mile to pair software with accessories for a more complete design experience.)

The bigger story is the phone's latest ColorOS software update (build A.25), which brings more features to the cover screen. Users can dictate replies to messages while the phone is closed, and a new Spotify widget offers prettier album art while also giving access to the heart/favorite toggle, and suggested playlists. (There's also a new WhatsApp widget, but I'm a Telegram guy.)

It's great to see Oppo evolving the Find N2 Flip, especially since Samsung has done very little since launch to update the feature set of its competing Galaxy Flip 4. Still, with every update Oppo drops, I can't help but think that so much more would be possible if the company would just let us run the full Android experience on that cover screen. What do you think?

For more on the Find N2 Flip, see my review from back in March on the MrMobile YouTube channel.

[Review samples provided by Oppo]

There's more to the Jelly Star, of course: it has a newer processor and a bigger battery alongside those ridiculous (albeit distinctive) LED strips. Selected favorites from a month with the Sony Xperia 1V. For this set I wanted to lean in to the Xperia's strengths: the 5.2x (125mm equivalent) optical zoom for the birds, bovine and butterflies; the high-speed burst capability to freeze the fireworks and stop-motion the splashes; and the new automatic processing to render sunset colors accurately, without washing them out into an HDR mudbath. 

By and large, the Xperia 1V delivered. Unbothered by the salt water spray of Block Island or the oppressive heat of late-summer Florida, the hardware held up better than any previous Sony I've tested. I'm happy to report that the company seems to have finally addressed its thermal performance problems: in a hot rec room, the phone shot almost 20 minutes of a ping-pong game in 4K without complaint. The battery *always* lasted all day long and often well into the next. And all the usual sweeteners are here too, including the most elaborate custom photography and cinematography software available on a phone.

My only complaints were the ones I always have with Sony phones: even the new-and-improved automatic processing often produces a flatter photo when put against other flagship Android phones – a shortcoming that becomes especially apparent when you're forced to use the terrible selfie camera. Also, after more than five years of the same design language, the Xperia long ago started to feel like a pretty stale smartphone. But hey – as the comments are, I'm sure, already reminding you: this is the last flagship phone you can buy with a 3.5mm headphone jack and a microSD slot, so there's that!

The Xperia 1V is available direct from Sony at $1299. (No MrMobile video, unfortunately, as I lost my review unit just as Techtember started descending upon us. Sorry, Sony – and sorry, all!)

Confession: I do not need the @teenageengineering TP-07 audio recorder. I conduct very few interviews, and when I do, Google's excellent software (built into my Pixel Fold) transcribes the audio automatically for later review. Nor do I need another item weighing down the Peak Design v2 that daily punishes my back, or another piece of equipment to remember to charge. (And I certainly didn't need to spend $1500 on the thing! 💸)

But the minute I saw it (probably in an Instagram ad, or some other piece of "content" in this feed-based war hell ride masquerading as the modern internet) I became obsessed. Design has played an increasingly pivotal role in my appreciation of modern technology - and teenage engineering was familiar to me as a key contributor to the ~vibe~ that makes the @nothing Phone 2 so special. 

The TP-07 oozes intentionality, and its single use case harkens back to a time before the smartphones became the convergence device that obliterated the humble "gadget." One of those gadgets was my first true tech obsession: a microcassette recorder that I carried around as a kid in the early 90s, recording the random goings-on of my preadolescent days ... just because I could. 

I'm taking the TP-07 to Cupertino to see if it helps me record higher-quality on-site audio during my Apple coverage next week, and I'll have a TP-07 video up on the channel sometime soon.

Even a mediocre camera can sing with a little help from Snapseed (or your photo editor of choice)!

Visited the @nathansawaya Lego Art exhibit in Raleigh this weekend, and shot brick pics with the camera I had on me: the Motorola Razr+.

Basically the most challenging environment imaginable for a smartphone camera: dark rooms with vibrant subjects illuminated by pinpoint spotlights with non-standard color temperatures! 😨 You can see how mightily the Razr struggled if you compare my edited photo 9/10 with the straight-outta-camera 10/10 shot.

But the Razr's foldable form factor meant I was able to capture a self-portrait with my gf for which I would otherwise have needed a tripod (3/10), and its external display meant she and I could help frame ourselves for 1, 5 and 8.

Bottom line: I wish flip phones didn't need to compromise their camera quality in exchange for their form factor, but if your workflow already includes editing most pics you post, foldables can be very useful nonetheless!

(Other bottom line: Lego art exhibits are awesome.)

Razr+ review sample provided by Motorola.

Every so often, I remember that some phones can cosplay as laptops, so I take a trip with the NexDock Wireless and see if it's gotten any better.

Sadly, it hasn't.

To be clear: it's incredible that a phone can even do this: wirelessly project its digital processing power onto a larger device, so you can use your phone with a more comfortable keyboard and a much larger screen. Manufacturers like Samsung, Huawei and Motorola (pictured here) also include custom software that transforms the phone interface into something better resembling a Chromebook. It's wondrous - in theory. 

But in practice, it's a long litany of disappointments, from the NexDock's poor speakers, cheap trackpad and middling battery life, to the stuttering and lag that comes along with the wireless connection. Toss in performance and compatibility issues when some Android apps are forced to run in desktop-style windows, and I've never ended a session like this without wishing I'd just brought a laptop along, like a normal person. 

Still, it's a cool peek into a kinda ... retro version of the future. And one day I hope my phone really will be performant enough to replace my computer. 

To learn why that's a hope of mine, and to see what happened when I tried a wired version of this with a Galaxy Fold a couple years back, check out my Samsung DeX road trip review on YouTube.

(Review units provided by NexDock and Motorola.)

#motorolareadyfor #motorolarazr #razr #nexdock #dex #samsungdex #laptop #tech

For the past two weeks, I've been sending iMessages ... from my Android phones! 🤯

Beeper *Mini* is a new app from the messaging company of the same name. You've been able to iMessage from Android using Beeper's service for a while now -- but until today, that capability has relied upon a cloud service using Beeper's hardware (essentially, a bunch of Mac minis functioning as a remote server).

By contrast, Beeper Mini is an entirely local app, connecting directly to Apple's servers and protecting its message traffic using end-to-end encryption. It provides the full suite of iMessage services (with the exception of location sharing) so Android folks can share in the fun of typing indicators, read receipts, full-resolution video sharing and group chats that don't suck. 

Over my two weeks of usage, I've found it to be reliable and quick, if a bit bare-bones in terms of design. It's functioned well on the OnePlus Open and Motorola Razr+, with only occasional bugs early in the experience that have since been squashed. My only large complaint thus far is the lack of quick-reply capability from the notification shade.

Beeper accomplished this feat by reverse engineering the iMessage platform, and its owner Eric Migicovsky told me that since reverse engineering is legal for the purposes of cross-compatibility, Apple doesn't have valid grounds for a lawsuit or cease & desist order. But as iMessage is one of the biggest bricks in the wall making up Apple's infamously impenetrable garden ... I do wonder how long it will be before it takes action to reinforce the exclusivity of its blue bubbles (through means legal, or technical).

Beeper Mini costs $1.99 per month and is available on the Play Store.
